<li id="cite_note-smc-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-smc_11-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFYang2004-5">Yang, H (2004-5). <a href="http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~jeharris/smc200_minutes" class="external text" title="http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~jeharris/smc200_minutes" rel="nofollow">"Lecture minutes for SMC 200Y: The Christian Imagination"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~jeharris/smc200_minutes" class="external free" title="http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~jeharris/smc200_minutes" rel="nofollow">http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~jeharris/smc200_minutes</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-08</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Lecture+minutes+for+SMC+200Y%3A+The+Christian+Imagination&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Yang&amp;rft.aufirst=H&amp;rft.au=Yang%2C+H&amp;rft.date=2004-5&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.chass.utoronto.ca%2F%7Ejeharris%2Fsmc200_minutes&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Aestheticization_of_violence"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.deutsche-bank-art.com/art/2005/3/e/2/333-2.php" class="external text" title="http://www.deutsche-bank-art.com/art/2005/3/e/2/333-2.php" rel="nofollow">"db artmag"</a>. Deutsche Bank Art. 2005<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.deutsche-bank-art.com/art/2005/3/e/2/333-2.php" class="external free" title="http://www.deutsche-bank-art.com/art/2005/3/e/2/333-2.php" rel="nofollow">http://www.deutsche-bank-art.com/art/2005/3/e/2/333-2.php</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-08</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=db+artmag&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.pub=Deutsche+Bank+Art&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.deutsche-bank-art.com%2Fart%2F2005%2F3%2Fe%2F2%2F333-2.php&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Aestheticization_of_violence"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-dworkin-13">^ <a href="#cite_ref-dworkin_13-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-dworkin_13-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFDworkin2006">Dworkin, Craig (2006-01-17). <a href="http://english.utah.edu/eclipse/Editor/DworkinTrotsky.pdf" class="external text" title="http://english.utah.edu/eclipse/Editor/DworkinTrotsky.pdf" rel="nofollow">"Trotsky's Hammer"</a> (PDF). Salt Lake City, UT: Department of English, University of Utah<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://english.utah.edu/eclipse/Editor/DworkinTrotsky.pdf" class="external free" title="http://english.utah.edu/eclipse/Editor/DworkinTrotsky.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://english.utah.edu/eclipse/Editor/DworkinTrotsky.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-08</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Trotsky%27s+Hammer&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Dworkin&amp;rft.aufirst=Craig&amp;rft.au=Dworkin%2C+Craig&amp;rft.date=2006-01-17&amp;rft.place=Salt+Lake+City%2C+UT&amp;rft.pub=Department+of+English%2C+University+of+Utah&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fenglish.utah.edu%2Feclipse%2FEditor%2FDworkinTrotsky.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Aestheticization_of_violence"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-kellner-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-kellner_14-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFKellner2005">Kellner, Douglas (2005-08-22). <a href="http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2005/entries/baudrillard/" class="external text" title="http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2005/entries/baudrillard/" rel="nofollow">"Jean Baudrillard"</a>. in Edward N. Zalta. <i>The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy</i> (Summer 2005 Edition ed.). Stanford, CA: The Metaphysics Research Lab, Center for the Study of Language and Information, <a href="/wiki/Stanford_University" title="Stanford University">Stanford University</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2005/entries/baudrillard/" class="external free" title="http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2005/entries/baudrillard/" rel="nofollow">http://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2005/entries/baudrillard/</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-08</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Jean+Baudrillard&amp;rft.atitle=The+Stanford+Encyclopedia+of+Philosophy&amp;rft.aulast=Kellner&amp;rft.aufirst=Douglas&amp;rft.au=Kellner%2C+Douglas&amp;rft.date=2005-08-22&amp;rft.edition=Summer+2005+Edition&amp;rft.place=Stanford%2C+CA&amp;rft.pub=The+Metaphysics+Research+Lab%2C+Center+for+the+Study+of+Language+and+Information%2C+%5B%5BStanford+University%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fplato.stanford.edu%2Farchives%2Fsum2005%2Fentries%2Fbaudrillard%2F&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Aestheticization_of_violence"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> In contrast, <a href="/w/index.php?title=Leonard_Berkowitz&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Leonard Berkowitz (page does not exist)">Leonard Berkowitz</a>'s (1977, 1986) "<a href="/w/index.php?title=Theory_of_Disinhibition&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Theory of Disinhibition (page does not exist)">Theory of Disinhibition</a>" proposes that while some people are naturally aggressive, they are usually able to repress this tendency. An obsessive interest in violent imagery in the cinema or on television may weaken their inhibitions and lead to a feeling that the release of their aggression is acceptable. This is allied to the "<a href="/w/index.php?title=Theory_of_Desensitisation&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Theory of Desensitisation (page does not exist)">Theory of Desensitisation</a>" which proposes that the consistent viewing of violent imagery gradually conditions viewers to accept violence as normal, i.e., it dulls their sensitivity to aggressive behaviour in everyday life.</li>
<li id="cite_note-16"><b><a href="#cite_ref-16" title="">^</a></b> Social learning theorists propose that some individuals learn aggressive behaviour by observing a <a href="/wiki/Role_model" title="Role model">role model</a>. Charismatic film and TV characters are, by definition, role models and suggestible people may imitate observed behaviour if they identify and empathise with the characters, and if the characters' behaviour is presented as justified. Hence, for example, explicit warnings of the danger of imitation are given before <a href="/wiki/World_Wrestling_Entertainment" title="World Wrestling Entertainment">World Wrestling Entertainment</a> (WWE) wrestling shows because the narrative context for the action emphasises the <i>good guys</i> and provides <i>vicarious reinforcement</i>; i.e. the acceptability of the violence is <i>reinforced</i> by being shown as benefitting the <i>good guy</i> as the aggressor. Such reinforcement is less likely in shows where the violence is shown as punished or unproductive. This confusion as to whether there are potential justifications for depicting violence aesthetically should lead us to the conclusion that it would be difficult to compose any set of criteria for judging acceptability in a censorship system. If censorship is nevertheless introduced, its operation would be uncertain and arbitrary, and subject to politicisation and manipulation by interest groups.<sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since February 2007" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup></li>
<li id="cite_note-crowder-17">^ <a href="#cite_ref-crowder_17-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-crowder_17-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFCrowder2006">Crowder, Matthew (2006). <a href="http://www.savingtheworld.co.uk/showPage.php?page=22" class="external text" title="http://www.savingtheworld.co.uk/showPage.php?page=22" rel="nofollow">"Aesthetics and Politics: Strange Days"</a>. <i>Saving The World</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.savingtheworld.co.uk/showPage.php?page=22" class="external free" title="http://www.savingtheworld.co.uk/showPage.php?page=22" rel="nofollow">http://www.savingtheworld.co.uk/showPage.php?page=22</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-08</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Aesthetics+and+Politics%3A+Strange+Days&amp;rft.atitle=Saving+The+World&amp;rft.aulast=Crowder&amp;rft.aufirst=Matthew&amp;rft.au=Crowder%2C+Matthew&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.savingtheworld.co.uk%2FshowPage.php%3Fpage%3D22&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Aestheticization_of_violence"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-cohen-18"><b><a href="#cite_ref-cohen_18-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFCohen1998">Cohen, Alexander J. (1998). <a href="http://cinemaspace.berkeley.edu/Cinema_Beyond/C_B.lectures/ClockworkOrange/Benj_CultIndustr_Clckwrk.html" class="external text" title="http://cinemaspace.berkeley.edu/Cinema_Beyond/C_B.lectures/ClockworkOrange/Benj_CultIndustr_Clckwrk.html" rel="nofollow">"Clockwork Orange and the Aestheticization of Violence"</a>. UC Berkeley Program in Film Studies<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://cinemaspace.berkeley.edu/Cinema_Beyond/C_B.lectures/ClockworkOrange/Benj_CultIndustr_Clckwrk.html" class="external free" title="http://cinemaspace.berkeley.edu/Cinema_Beyond/C_B.lectures/ClockworkOrange/Benj_CultIndustr_Clckwrk.html" rel="nofollow">http://cinemaspace.berkeley.edu/Cinema_Beyond/C_B.lectures/ClockworkOrange/Benj_CultIndustr_Clckwrk.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-06-08</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Clockwork+Orange+and+the+Aestheticization+of+Violence&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Cohen&amp;rft.aufirst=Alexander+J.&amp;rft.au=Cohen%2C+Alexander+J.&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft.pub=UC+Berkeley+Program+in+Film+Studies&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcinemaspace.berkeley.edu%2FCinema_Beyond%2FC_B.lectures%2FClockworkOrange%2FBenj_CultIndustr_Clckwrk.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Aestheticization_of_violence"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
